@node "use" "What do I do?"

 Well, it's pretty self-explanatory, but I needed to fill some space
 in this Guide, so:

 Installation:

 * Just put the whole drawer somewhere
   If you don't want the source, it's OK to delete it, as
   well as the ".xtra" file that goes with it, and the
   "gad.shps" file as well...


 Usage:

 * Double Click the Icon -

 -> If you have ReqTools:

   You will see a control panel with some gadgets and an output
   window just below.

   * The first time you run it, click on the "Scan Libs" button.
     You should also do this whenever you add new libraries, or
     otherwise change your Blitz library setup, or acidlibs.
   
     The program will look through your Blitz libraries, make a
     datalist file with all the library numbers and commands.  It
     will also report any duplicate library numbers encountered.
     This list will be saved into the "Investigator" directory.
     You can, of course, use this list for other things.  It is
     a standard ascii text file.

     It's interesting to have a look at this file in a text reader.
     I bet you find a few commands you didn't know you had  ;)

   * Now you are ready to investigate a tokenized Blitz source.
     Click the "Scan Source" button - you will get a file requester
     asking for the name of the source to scan.  Once you have
     selected one, you get a second file requester, asking where to
     save the investigation report.  The default is to save it back
     in the same place as the source, with ".RPT" tacked on the end.
     If you select "Cancel", no report will be saved to disk, but the
     results will be shown in the window.

     If you request a report to disk, you will then get a third requester.
     This asks for a directory to store two temporary files.  The default
     location is T:
     These files are used to create the full cross reference.   If you
     cancel this requester, only a simple count of commands will be
     produced.

     NOTE.   It takes significantly longer to produce a full cross
     reference.   Up to six times as long.   This is because it is
     writing a record for each token encountered.   You may wish to
     do a simple report first - particularly with big sources.

     The full cross reference is only saved to disk.   The on-screen
     report is the same for both options.

     - To cancel a report before it is finished, click on the "Inspector"
     button.
    
     - You can also click the "Inspector" gadget when it is "at rest"
     (plain background) to see the "About" information.


   * You can also get a listing of the available unused library numbers
     on your system by clicking the "Lib #'s" button. 

 -> Oh, and if you DON'T have ReqTools, you will most likely get a nice
    black screen with a flashing red box - but EVERYBODY has ReqTools by
    now, don't they?
@endnode

@node "bugs" "Bugs  :("

  No, it's not perfect...

  What did you expect for free  ;)

  The problem:

    Some libraries (mostly in the acidlibs file) return the wrong
    command numbers.

    I'm hoping this is due to some obvious mistake I've made in my
    code, which I'm sure you'll point out to me...

    Anyway, I've "fixed" it by patching the library reading routine
    to throw in some extra command names where needed.

    This works with my version of Acidlibs  (the latest one), but I
    have no idea if it will work with any other versions.

    The bug will show up as some wrong command names being shown in
    the report.

  Also:

    In spite of the purpose of the program, I haven't used it on 
    itself yet  ;)

    In other words, it isn't optimized.  I was hoping to work out
    that token-reading bit first.
@endnode

